        cons: ['Pitch is heavily focused on beautiful structural design; it completely lacks the insanely complex, dense data-visualization and charting capabilities required by Wall Street bankers living in Excel/PowerPoint', 'The absolute rigidity of the "smart formatting" can slightly frustrate hardcore graphic designers who want total, chaotic freedom to place elements anywhere', 'Offline capabilities exist but are secondary; Pitch is undeniably a cloud-first, browser-centric application requiring an internet connection to truly shine', 'Animations and complex slide transitions are intentionally restrained compared to the cinematic capabilities of Apple Keynote'],
        pricing_overview: `<p>Pitch offers an exceptionally generous Free tier that allows teams to build full decks collaboratively and utilize standard templates (with a small Pitch watermark). Upgrading to the professional SaaS tiers (Pro, Business) removes the watermark, unlocks heavy workspace analytics, introduces massive video-upload limits, and provides deep, custom brand access control.</p>`,
        comparison_summary: `<p>Pitch competes fiercely with Tome, Gamma, and the legacy giants (PowerPoint/Google Slides). Tome is highly narrative, experimental, and focused heavily on a fluid, "mobile-first" scrolling aesthetic. Gamma is the master of extremely rapid AI outlining. PowerPoint remains the king of absolute desktop corporate charting. Pitch differentiates itself by being the ultimate *Modern Replacement*. It marries the familiar, horizontal slide structure of PowerPoint with the breathtaking modern UI and multiplayer mechanics of Figma, augmented by AI text-generation—making it the undisputed standard weapon for modern venture capital pitches.</p>`
